\includegraphics[max width=\textwidth, center]{2023_09_22_07b4d66e23971ccb85c0g-07_1229_1839_234_1886}

Fig. 2 (a) O 1s, and (b) C 1s, regions of the XPS spectrum of the CuCo surface alloy (20\% Co-80\% Cu) under various CO pressures. The attenuated peak intensities at higher gas pressure are due to increased scattering of photoelectrons by gas phase molecules. The surface is initially covered with oxygen, which produces the peak at $529.9 \mathrm{eV}$. The $\mathrm{C}$ and $\mathrm{O}$ peaks from $\mathrm{CO}_{\text {ads }}$ appear at $531.9 \mathrm{eV}$ and $285.7 \mathrm{eV}$, similar to those of $\mathrm{CO}_{\text {ads }}$ on Co (Figure S1). The gas phase CO peaks are shown enclosed by a dashed box, their exact position depanding on the surface work function. The graphs in (c) show the coverage of $\mathrm{CO}(\bullet)$ and O ( $\boldsymbol{\square})$ vs CO presssure. The CO reacts and removes O from the surface at appreciable rates above $0.01$ Torr. The CO coverage on pure $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$ in equilibirum with the $\mathrm{CO}$ pressure is shown for reference $(\times)$. The box on the right shows the coverage after evacuation (Vac), and after heating to $400 \mathrm{~K}$. Coverage of different species as a function of pressure in (c) was determined from the O 1s peak intensities with respect to the $\mathrm{Cu} 2 \mathrm{p}$ + Co $2 \mathrm{p}$ peak intensities measured at the same kinetic energy, and using the wellknown $0.5$ ML coverage of the $(2 \times 1)$ oxide structure as reference. Since the XPS peaks of CO/CuCo (Figures 2a and b) are similar to those on CO/Co (Figure S1 of the Supporting Information (SI)), we conclude that the majority of the CO molecules are bound to $\mathrm{Co}$, or to $\mathrm{Cu}$ atoms modified by binding to Co. DFT calculations and other experimental techniques discussed below show that the former case is correct. Since the Co coverage is $\sim 0.2 \mathrm{ML}$, this implies that more than one CO molecule is bound per Co atom on average. This interesting and unexpected result is in line with a 3-decades old result of CO adsorption on Co clusters deposited on $\mathrm{Cu}(100)$, obtained with AES and thermal desorption spectroscopy. ${ }^{36}$

The changes in the chemical state of Co due to CO adsorption were followed by the shifts in binding energy (BE) of its $2 \mathrm{p}_{3 / 2}$ core levels and by the changing intensities of the $\mathrm{Co}^{0}$ and $\mathrm{Co}^{2+}$ components, as shown in Figure 3. The intensities of the $\mathrm{Co}^{0}$ and $\mathrm{Co}^{2+}$ peaks and their satellites were measured by fitting them according to the procedure suggested in Ref. ${ }^{37}$ (examples shown by the red and blue curves for the UHV spectra). We find that initially about half of the Co appears as $\mathrm{Co}^{2+}$, located on the top M-O rows, whilst the other half, corresponding to $\mathrm{Co}^{\circ}$, is located in the second layer. This ratio remained unchanged under CO gas up to $0.01$ Torr where it started to decrease (Figure 3b) due to reduction of the $\mathrm{Co}^{2+}$. At $0.5$ Torr reduction to the metallic state proceeds rapidly, and only small amounts of $\mathrm{Co}^{2+}$ remain (Figure 3b). The $\mathrm{Cu}$ atoms on the other hand are fully reduced at this pressure. ${ }^{38}$ Particularly interesting is the shift in the $\mathrm{Co}^{0} 2 \mathrm{p}_{3 / 2}$ $\mathrm{BE}$ observed in these experiments, where the Co coverage is $0.2 \mathrm{ML}$ (Figure 3c black dots). At Co coverages above $0.5 \mathrm{ML}$ (red dots), where Co and CoO form larger islands, no shift was observed. The shift of the Co $2 \mathrm{p}_{3 / 2}$ peak to a higher BE indicates an increasing donation of electrons from Co to CO, which we ascribe to binding of multiple CO molecules per Co atom, similar to the structure of Co-carbonyl species. This is only possible if Co is in the form of isolated atoms or few atom clusters where the bound CO molecules can fan out to accommodate their steric repulsion. As we show below DFT calculations indicate that the Co atoms in the second layer are pulled out to the top layer by CO chemisorption, where it forms small clusters.\\
\includegraphics[max width=\textwidth, center]{2023_09_22_07b4d66e23971ccb85c0g-09_238_1094_239_1223}

Fig. 3 (a) Co $2 \mathrm{p}_{3 / 2}$ XP spectra acquired at RT as a function of increasing CO pressure, from UHV (bottom black spectrum) to $0.5$ Torr (brown). The two spectra at the top were collected after CO evacuation (pink) and after heating the sample to $400 \mathrm{~K}$ (top, dark yellow). Co $2 \mathrm{p}_{3 / 2}$ has satellite peaks from $\mathrm{Co}^{0}$ and $\mathrm{Co}^{2+}$, were fitted with the red $\left(\mathrm{Co}^{0}\right)$ and blue $\left(\mathrm{Co}^{2+}\right)$ curves, shown only for the initial spectrum in UHV (bottom). The amount of $\mathrm{Co}^{2+}$ decreases above $0.01$ Torr (b), while CO coverage increases (c). The Co XPS peaks shift to higher binding energy (black curve in (c)), following the increasing number of CO molecules per Co atom at low Co coverage. No XPS shifts were observed when the Co coverage was $>0.5 \mathrm{ML}$ (red dots in (c)) due to steric contraints preventing multiple CO binding per Co atom (except possibly at island edge atoms).

In agreement with XPS, the STM images confirmed the removal of the oxide structure on the surface as the CO pressure increased (Figures S5-S6). After the $(2 \times 1)$ oxide structure is removed the surface is covered with 2D nanoclusters of irregular shape (Figure S7). Figure 4 shows an atomically resolved image, where the clusters appear as dimer rows at pressures above $0.5$ Torr. The dimers appear as pairs of bright spots along the [110] direction separated by $3.5 \AA$, substantially larger than the atomic lattice spacing of $2.55 \AA$. We explain this by assigning the maxima to CO molecules that are adsorbed on the top sites and tilted away from each other due to steric repulsion. On the [001] direction the periodicity is $3 \AA$, which is less that the atomic periodicity $3.61 \AA$ in that direction. We attribute this adsorption geometry to the formation of locally dense CO structures with more than one molecule per Co atom, as shown schematically in Figure 4c. From IRRAS (see below) we know that CO adsorbs both on top and on bridge Co sites, so that the observed STM contrast can originate from combinations of 3 CO (2 top sites, 1 bridge site) and 5 CO (4 top sites, 1 bridge site) molecules. According to our model in Figure 4c, CO molecules at the bridge sites have a very low STM contrast, because in mixed top and bridge or hollow CO sites, the STM contrast is dominated by that of the top sites. ${ }^{12,39-40}$ While from STM imaging only it is not possible to prove this at present, both IR spectra and DFT calculations (shown later) indicate that CO molecules occupy both atop and bridge sites simultaneously. In fact, DFT calculations support this model by showing that isolated 2-Co-atom clusters accommodating $5 \mathrm{CO}$ molecules are energetically favored.

