\section{XPS Calibration of Surface Co Coverage}
The Co coverage on the surface of the $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$ crystal was measured using the XPS peak intensities. Similar to deposition rate measurements with QCM, the Co surface layer underneath the oxygen top layer is calculated to have $21 \%$ Co and $79 \% \mathrm{Cu}$ using the XPS $\mathrm{Cu} 2 \mathrm{p}$ and Co $2 \mathrm{p}$ peak intensities (85:15) and the Strohmeier equation [S1]. The 85:15 ratio remained unchanged throughout the experiments indicating Co neither desorbs via forming a carbonyl at pressures up to $0.5$ Torr of CO nor it diffuses into the bulk.

\section{CO Adsorption - Reference $O$ 1s and C 1s Spectra}
In this section, we compare the core level $\mathrm{O}$ 1s and $\mathrm{C}$ 1s spectra of CO adsorption on three surface: 1- our alloy CuCo surface, 2- a bare $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$ surface, and 3- a 10 ML Co thin film. The latter two are used as references for the pure $\mathrm{Cu}$ and $\mathrm{Co}$ metals.

Figure S1 shows an example of XPS spectra collected during CO adsorption on the surface, as well as reference measurements of $\mathrm{CO}$ adsorption on $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$ and on a thin Co film. On $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$, peaks arising from $\mathrm{CO}$ adsorption are at around $531.1 \mathrm{eV}$, and $286.1 \mathrm{eV}$ with a strong satellite at $288.4 \mathrm{eV}$ [27]. This strong satellite feature in the C 1s region is due to weak chemisorption of CO on Cu [S2]. On the $10 \mathrm{ML}$ Co film, CO peaks appear at $531.7$ and $285.7 \mathrm{eV}$ without any satellite features. On the CuCo surface, the CO peaks appear at $531.9 \mathrm{eV}$ and $285.7$ $\mathrm{eV}$, indicating that $\mathrm{CO} / \mathrm{CuCo}$ has the same peak position as $\mathrm{CO} / \mathrm{Co}$ in the $\mathrm{O} 1 \mathrm{~s}$ region and peak position somewhere between CO/Co and $\mathrm{CO} / \mathrm{Cu}$ in the $\mathrm{C} 1$ s region. However, in the $\mathrm{C} 1$ s region no satellite peak was observed for CO adsorbed on CuCo, which is an indicative of strong chemisorption (weaker than on pure Co but stronger than on pure $\mathrm{Cu}$ ) [S2]. Both observations suggest that there are only few $\mathrm{CO}$ molecules are adsorbed on bare $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$, which occupies $79 \%$ of the surface.

