\section{S3- HPSTM}
Bare $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$

We start with discussing the structural changes on a bare $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$ surface in the presence of 1 Torr of CO at RT, which was discussed in detailed in our previous work [14]. We have reported that this surface breaks up into clusters a few nanometer long oriented along the [1-10] direction and separated by typically two atomic distances, i.e., $0.72 \mathrm{~nm}$ in the [100] direction with $(1 \times 2)$ periodicity. This restructuring of the $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$ surface in the presence of $\mathrm{CO}$ is different than that of the model $\operatorname{CuCo}(110)$ surface used in the present work (Figure 4).

\section{CuCo before Reduction}
As shown in our previous work, $\mathrm{p}(2 \times 1)-\mathrm{O}$ reconstruction on $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$ remains for long times at CO pressures below $0.02$ Torr at $298 \mathrm{~K}$ [32] due to high binding energy of atomic oxygen in the added rows (around $2 \mathrm{eV}$ ) [S3]. This is also partially the case for the CuCo surface. Examples are shown in the low and high magnification HPSTM images in Figure S6a and b, respectively. It is not clear from these images if the clusters on the surface are pure Co (i.e., phase separation), or they are the initial nano-islands formed during the sample preparation process. However, there is a considerable amount of adsorbed CO $(0.13 \mathrm{ML})$ already at $0.01$ Torr on this surface compared to $\mathrm{Cu}(110)-\mathrm{p}(2 \times 1)-\mathrm{O}$ which was below $0.01 \mathrm{ML}$ (coverages estimated from APXPS measurements) [14, 32]. CO probably adsorbs on Co rich parts and breaks the (2×1) periodicity. The surface does not exhibit this periodicity in Figure S6b are Co, although CO may have not entirely removed the initial oxygen attached to it. In summary, the surface is a mixture of ordered $\mathrm{O}$ on $\mathrm{Cu}(110)$ and disordered $\mathrm{O}+\mathrm{CO}$ on $\mathrm{Co}$ in this pressure range.

