\section{S4- DFT}
\section{Gibbs Free Energy Formalism}
We use surface Gibbs free energies - a formalism extensively employed to study materials under working conditions [S4-S5] - to compare the stability of different CO/CuCo phases, with the following formulation: the Gibbs free energy $\Delta G(\theta, \chi)$ of the $\mathrm{CO} / \mathrm{CuCo}$ system depends on the CO coverage, $\theta$, defined as the number of CO molecules per area unit, and the Co surface percent population, $\chi$, defined as the number of Co atoms at the surface with respect to the total number of Co atoms in the cell. We computed surface Gibbs free energies $\Delta G(\theta, \chi)$ according to Eq. 1

$\Delta \mathrm{G}(\theta, \chi)=\left(\mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{CO}-\mathrm{CuCo}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{Cu}} \mathrm{E}^{\mathrm{Bulk}}{ }_{\mathrm{Cu}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{Co}} \mathrm{E}^{\mathrm{Bulk}}{ }_{\mathrm{Co}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{CO}} \mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{CO}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{CO}} \mathrm{T} \Delta \mathrm{S}_{\mathrm{ads}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{CO}} \mathrm{k}_{\mathrm{b}} \mathrm{TLn}\left(\mathrm{p} / p^{0}\right)\right) / \mathrm{A}$ where $E_{C O-C u C o}, E^{B u l k}{ }_{C u}$ and $E^{\text {Bulk }}{ }_{C u}$ are respectively the total energy of the alloy-for a given $\chi$ solute distribution-and the total energy of bulk $\mathrm{Cu}$ and $\mathrm{Co} . E_{C O}$, on the other hand is the total energy of gas CO. $N_{C u}, N_{C o}$ and $N_{C O}$ are the number of $\mathrm{Cu}$ and $\mathrm{Co}$ atoms in the unit cell, and the number of $\mathrm{CO}$ molecules in the $\mathrm{CO} / \mathrm{CuCo}$ system. $T$ is the temperature and $p$ is the $\mathrm{CO}$ pressure with respect to the standard pressure $p^{0}$ equal to 1 atm. $k_{b}$ is the Boltzmann constant and $A$ is the area of the unit cell $\left(73.72 \AA^{2}\right)$. We referred the $\Delta \mathrm{G}$ values with respect to the surface energy value for the most stable solute arrangement $\left(93 \mathrm{meV} / \AA^{2}\right) . \Delta S_{a d s}$ is the entropy change for the adsorption defined as in

$\Delta \mathrm{S}_{\mathrm{ads}}=\left(\mathrm{S}_{\mathrm{CO}-\mathrm{CuCo}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{Cu}} \mathrm{S}_{\mathrm{Cu}}^{\mathrm{Bulk}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{Co}} \mathrm{S}_{\mathrm{Co}}^{\mathrm{Bulk}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{CO}} \mathrm{S}_{\mathrm{CO}}^{0}\right)$

we assume $\mathrm{S}_{\mathrm{CO}-\mathrm{CuCo}} \sim \mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{CO}} \mathrm{S}^{\mathrm{Ads}}{ }_{\mathrm{CO}+} \mathrm{S}_{\mathrm{CuCo}}$ and neglect the formation entropy of the alloy in comparison to the gas adsorbate so that $\Delta S_{a d s}$ becomes

$\Delta \mathrm{S}_{\mathrm{ads}}=\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{CO}}\left(\mathrm{S}^{\mathrm{Ads}} \mathrm{co}^{0} \mathrm{~S}_{\mathrm{CO}}^{0}\right)$.

In Eq. $3 S_{C O}^{0}$ is the standard entropy of gas $\mathrm{CO}(195 \mathrm{~J} / \mathrm{molK}$ at $273 \mathrm{~K}$ in agreement with NIST [S6]) and $S^{A d s}$ co is the entropy of adsorbed CO. We used the empirical relationship developed by Campbell [S7] to describe the entropy of adsorbed adsorbates: $\mathrm{S}^{\mathrm{Ads}} \mathrm{CO}^{\sim 0.7} \mathrm{~S}^{0} \mathrm{CO}$.

In order to construct $\Delta \mathrm{G}$ maps (Figure 6) we studied CO-CuCo structures with increasing Co surface population $\chi$, from zero for the case in which all Co is located in the subsurface to $100 \%$ when both Co atoms in the unit cell populate the Cu matrix surface. At each $\chi$ value we addressed the adsorption of CO for a range of increasing coverage, from zero to 1ML. For each coverage, we found the most stable adsorption arrangement for $\mathrm{CO}$ in the CuCo cell, considering all possible $\mathrm{Cu}$ and $\mathrm{Co}$ adsorption sites. That gave a grid of (7x3) $\Delta \mathrm{G}$ values. A continues $\Delta \mathrm{G}$ map was created by interpolating the Gibbs free energy values in the grid. We report average binding energies $E_{b}$ in Table $\mathrm{S} 2$ for all structures in the $\Delta \mathrm{G}$ grid and the atomistic structures of the CO-CuCo phases are displayed in Figure $\mathrm{S} 8 . E_{b}$ were all computed with respect to the most stable CuCo arrangement in the absence of $\mathrm{CO}$ as in

$\mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{b}}=\left(\mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{CO}-\mathrm{CuCo}}-\mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{CuCo}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{CO}} \mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{CO}}\right) / \mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{CO}}$

