We finally address the structure of $\mathrm{CO} / \mathrm{CuCo}$ in the presence of $\mathrm{CO}$ at ambient temperature and pressure conditions. Figure S9 (Left Panel) shows a free surface energy plot $\Delta \mathrm{G}$ $(\Delta \mu)$ as a function of the CO chemical potential of $\Delta \mu$,

$\Delta \mathrm{G}(\Delta \mu)=\left(\mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{CO}-\mathrm{CuCo}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{Cu}} \mathrm{E}_{\mathrm{Cu}}^{\mathrm{Bulk}}-\mathrm{N}_{\mathrm{Co}} \mathrm{E}^{\mathrm{Bulk}}{ }_{\mathrm{Co}}-\Delta \mu\right) / \mathrm{A}$

Figure S9 include all CO/CuCo structures at increasing CO coverage at different Co surface populations. This is contrast to Figure 7 in which only the most stable CO-CuCo phases are visible. For low CO chemical potential, the most stable phase is the bare CuCo substrate with Co atoms populating the subsurface. The adsorption of CO only starts once $\Delta \mu$ reaches the critical value of $1.5 \mathrm{eV}$. At moderate and high $\Delta \mu$ values, CO molecules adsorb on the Co sites leading to $0.5 \mathrm{ML}$ and $0.75 \mathrm{ML}$. Our results indicate that $\mathrm{CO} / \mathrm{CuCo}$ phases with $0.75 \mathrm{ML} \mathrm{CO}$ coverage are present in the phase diagram at ambient conditions, containing of five $\mathrm{CO}$ molecules bonded to the Co sites and a single CO molecule bonded to Cu. The average C-O distance in the 5CO-Co moiety is $1.18 \AA$ (molecules 1-5 in Figure S10 Top panel), being this distance $1.14 \AA$ for the CO molecule bonded to Cu (molecule 6 in Figure S10 Top panel). Both distances are slightly larger than for the case of gas $\mathrm{CO}(1.13 \AA)$. The average C-Co distance is $1.79 \AA$ for the top CO molecules in the 5CO-Co moiety (molecules 1, 2, 3 and 5 in Figure S10 Top panel), being $1.93$ A for the bridge CO (molecule 4 in Figure S10 Top panel). The C-Co distance for the CO bonded to $\mathrm{Cu}$ is $1.86 \AA$ (molecule 6 in Figure S10 Top panel). We found in the experiments that the adsorption of CO pulls the Co atoms away from the surface. The average vertical distance of the Co atoms with respect to the outermost $\operatorname{CuCo}(110)$ plane is $0.51 \AA$.\\
